`timeout(ms)` from ember-concurrency is a cancelation-aware delay that pauses the task for the specified number of milliseconds. Unlike `new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, ms))`, `timeout()` respects task cancellation — if the task is cancelled while waiting, `timeout()` stops immediately, preventing memory leaks.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency'
import { registerDestructor } from '@ember/destroyable'

export default class LiveScorePollerComponent extends Component {
  @tracked liveScore = null

  constructor(owner, args) {
    super(owner, args)
    this.pollLiveScore.perform()
    registerDestructor(this, () => this.pollLiveScore.cancelAll())
  }

  pollLiveScore = task(async () => {
    while (true) {
      const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${this.args.matchId}/live-score`)
      this.liveScore = await response.json()
      await timeout(5000) // Wait 5 seconds between polls
    }
  })

  <template>
    {{#if this.liveScore}}
      <p>{{this.liveScore.runs}}/{{this.liveScore.wickets}}</p>
      <p>Overs: {{this.liveScore.overs}}</p>
    {{else}}
      <p>Loading live score...</p>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```
A `while (true)` loop combined with `timeout()` creates a clean polling pattern. The task runs indefinitely, fetching data and waiting between each cycle. Because `timeout()` is cancellation-aware, the entire loop stops cleanly when `cancelAll()` is called — no dangling timers or requests remain.

