Glimmer's template engine tracks which `@tracked` cells are read during rendering. Since ember-concurrency's task properties (`isRunning`, `last`, etc.) are backed by `@tracked` cells, Glimmer automatically registers them as dependencies. When the task transitions state (running → complete), the tracked cells mutate, Glimmer detects the invalidation, and queues a re-render. You get loading/error/success state management with zero boilerplate — no manual `@tracked isLoading`, no `try/catch` state resets.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'

export default class MultiMatchLoader extends Component {
  @tracked activeInstances = []

  loadMatch = task(async (matchId) => {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}`)
    return await res.json()
  })

  startLoad = (matchId) => {
    // perform() returns a TaskInstance — store it for individual cancel
    const instance = this.loadMatch.perform(matchId)
    this.activeInstances = [...this.activeInstances, instance]
  }

  cancelOne = (instance) => {
    instance.cancel() // cancel ONLY this specific instance
  }

  cancelAll = () => {
    this.loadMatch.cancelAll() // cancel ALL running instances
  }

  <template>
    {{#each this.activeInstances as |instance|}}
      <div>
        {{#if instance.isRunning}}
          <button {{on "click" (fn this.cancelOne instance)}}>Cancel</button>
        {{else}}
          <span>{{instance.value.teams.home}} vs {{instance.value.teams.away}}</span>
        {{/if}}
      </div>
    {{/each}}
    <button {{on "click" this.cancelAll}}>Cancel All</button>
  </template>
}
```

Calling `instance.cancel()` cancels only that specific execution, leaving other concurrent instances running. Calling `task.cancelAll()` cancels every running and queued instance of that task simultaneously. Store `perform()` return values when you need per-instance cancel buttons (e.g., a list of cancellable downloads). Use `cancelAll()` for "stop everything" actions like navigating away or resetting a view.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'

export default class SubmitScoreCard extends Component {
  // ❌ Async method — no cancellation, no built-in state, leaks on destroy
  @tracked isSaving = false
  @tracked saveError = null

  async saveScoreManual(data) {
    this.isSaving = true
    this.saveError = null
    try {
      await fetch('/api/scores', { method: 'POST', body: JSON.stringify(data) })
    } catch (e) {
      this.saveError = e // might run after component destroyed!
    } finally {
      this.isSaving = false // might run after component destroyed!
    }
  }

  // ✅ task() — cancellable, reactive state, lifecycle-safe, no boilerplate
  saveScore = task({ drop: true }, async (data) => {
    await fetch('/api/scores', { method: 'POST', body: JSON.stringify(data) })
  })

  <template>
    {{#if this.saveScore.isRunning}}<span>Saving...</span>{{/if}}
    {{#if this.saveScore.last.error}}
      <p>{{this.saveScore.last.error.message}}</p>
    {{/if}}
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.saveScore this.args.scoreData)}}>Save</button>
  </template>
}
```

Async methods have four problems: (1) no cancellation — they run to completion even after component destruction; (2) no built-in state — you need separate `@tracked` variables; (3) no concurrency control — double-clicks create parallel runs; (4) potential errors from updating destroyed component state. `task()` solves all four: auto-cancelled on destroy, built-in reactive state, concurrency modifiers for double-click protection, and safe cleanup via `finally`.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task, taskGroup } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class MatchDataTabs extends Component {
  // OPTION A: taskGroup drop — the GROUP allows only 1 total running at a time
  loadingGroup = taskGroup({ drop: true })

  fetchScore = task({ group: this.loadingGroup }, async () => {
    return await fetch('/api/score').then(r => r.json())
  })

  fetchLineup = task({ group: this.loadingGroup }, async () => {
    return await fetch('/api/lineup').then(r => r.json())
  })
  // If fetchScore is running, performing fetchLineup is DROPPED

  // OPTION B: each task has its own drop — independent of each other
  fetchScoreIndependent = task({ drop: true }, async () => {
    return await fetch('/api/score').then(r => r.json())
  })

  fetchLineupIndependent = task({ drop: true }, async () => {
    return await fetch('/api/lineup').then(r => r.json())
  })
  // Both can run SIMULTANEOUSLY — each just prevents its own duplicates

  <template>
    <p>Group loading: {{this.loadingGroup.isRunning}}</p>
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.fetchScore)}}>Score</button>
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.fetchLineup)}}>Lineup</button>
  </template>
}
```

With `taskGroup({ drop: true })`, the drop limit applies across ALL tasks in the group collectively — only one task from the group runs at a time, regardless of which task is triggered. With per-task `drop`, each task only prevents its own duplicates, so two different tasks can run concurrently. Use `taskGroup` when operations are mutually exclusive (loading different panels of the same UI section) and per-task `drop` when operations are independent.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'

export default class PlayerTypeahead extends Component {
  @tracked results = []

  // restartable = "always search for the LATEST query"
  search = task({ restartable: true }, async (query) => {
    // Debounce: if user types again within 250ms, this await is cancelled
    await timeout(250)

    // Network: if user types again during fetch, this is cancelled
    const res = await fetch(`/api/players/search?q=${encodeURIComponent(query)}`)
    return await res.json()
  })

  handleInput = (e) => {
    this.search.perform(e.target.value)
  }

  <template>
    <input {{on "input" this.handleInput}} placeholder="Search player..." />
    {{#if this.search.isRunning}}
      <span class="text-gray-400">Searching...</span>
    {{else}}
      {{#each this.search.last.value as |player|}}
        <div>{{player.name}} — {{player.team}}</div>
      {{/each}}
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```

For search, you only ever care about results for the *most recent* query. `restartable` cancels the previous search the moment a new character is typed — no stale results from an older query can overwrite the current one. Combined with `timeout()` for debouncing, you get a complete typeahead with one modifier and zero explicit AbortController or cleanup code. `drop` would be wrong here (it would ignore new keystrokes while searching), and `enqueue` would be wrong (it would run old queries needlessly).

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'

export default class ScorecardEditor extends Component {
  @tracked scorecard = { ...this.args.scorecard }

  // keepLatest: saves current state, then runs ONCE MORE with the final state
  autoSave = task({ keepLatest: true }, async (data) => {
    await timeout(500) // small delay to batch rapid changes
    await fetch('/api/scorecard', {
      method: 'PUT',
      body: JSON.stringify(data)
    })
  })

  updateField = (field, value) => {
    this.scorecard = { ...this.scorecard, [field]: value }
    // Each keystroke calls perform() — only latest queued call executes after current save
    this.autoSave.perform(this.scorecard)
  }

  <template>
    <input
      value={{this.scorecard.batsman}}
      {{on "input" (fn this.updateField "batsman")}}
    />
    <span class="text-sm text-gray-500">
      {{#if this.autoSave.isRunning}}Saving...{{else}}Saved ✓{{/if}}
    </span>
  </template>
}
```

`keepLatest` solves the auto-save dilemma: you don't want to cancel a save in progress (data loss risk), but you also don't want to queue every single keystroke (N+1 requests). It lets the current save finish, then executes *exactly one more* with the latest data. This guarantees the final state is always saved with at most 2 total requests regardless of how many keystrokes occurred, giving you both data integrity and efficiency.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class BallByBallRecorder extends Component {
  // enqueue: every perform() runs in order, none dropped
  recordEvent = task({ enqueue: true }, async (event) => {
    const res = await fetch('/api/ball-events', {
      method: 'POST',
      body: JSON.stringify(event)
    })
    const saved = await res.json()
    console.log(`Saved event ${saved.id}: ${event.type}`)
    return saved
  })

  // Usage: rapid fire from scorers clicking buttons
  recordWide = () => this.recordEvent.perform({ type: 'wide', runs: 1 })
  recordBoundary = () => this.recordEvent.perform({ type: 'boundary', runs: 4 })
  recordWicket = () => this.recordEvent.perform({ type: 'wicket' })

  <template>
    <p>Pending: {{this.recordEvent.numQueued}}</p>
    <button {{on "click" this.recordWide}}>Wide</button>
    <button {{on "click" this.recordBoundary}}>4</button>
    <button {{on "click" this.recordWicket}}>Wicket</button>
  </template>
}
```

`enqueue` is preferable to manual Promise chaining because it's dynamic — you can add new items to the queue at any time without restructuring your code. Manual chaining (`p = p.then(...)`) is fragile: it's hard to inspect queue length, hard to cancel individual items, and requires a reference chain that grows unbounded. `enqueue` gives you `numQueued`, individual instance cancellation, and automatic cleanup on component destruction — all impossible with manual chaining.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class TournamentStatsFetcher extends Component {
  // maxConcurrency: run up to 4 fetches at once, queue the rest
  fetchTeamStats = task({ enqueue: true, maxConcurrency: 4 }, async (teamId) => {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/teams/${teamId}/stats`)
    return await res.json()
  })

  loadAllTeams = () => {
    // 16 teams — runs 4 at a time, queues the rest
    this.args.teamIds.forEach(id => this.fetchTeamStats.perform(id))
  }

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" this.loadAllTeams}}>Load All Teams</button>
    <p>
      Running: {{this.fetchTeamStats.numRunning}} /
      Queued: {{this.fetchTeamStats.numQueued}}
    </p>
    {{#if this.fetchTeamStats.lastSuccessful}}
      <p>Last loaded: {{this.fetchTeamStats.lastSuccessful.value.teamName}}</p>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```

`maxConcurrency` without `enqueue` only drops extras, so it's almost always paired with `enqueue` to queue rather than discard. The combination `{ enqueue: true, maxConcurrency: N }` creates a worker pool: N tasks run simultaneously, remaining calls queue up and start as slots free. Without `maxConcurrency`, `enqueue` runs tasks one at a time (maxConcurrency implicitly 1). Setting `maxConcurrency: 4` is like having 4 parallel fetch workers — controlled throughput without overwhelming the server.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'

export default class SafeScoreUpdater extends Component {
  @tracked score = null

  loadScore = task({ restartable: true }, async (matchId) => {
    await timeout(2000) // simulates slow fetch
    const res = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/score`)
    const data = await res.json()

    // If task was cancelled (restartable = new perform() arrived),
    // execution NEVER reaches this line — assignment doesn't happen
    this.score = data // safe: only runs if task completes normally
    return data
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.loadScore "m1")}}>Load M1</button>
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.loadScore "m2")}}>Load M2</button>
    {{! Clicking M2 while M1 loads cancels M1 — M1's result never sets this.score }}
    <p>{{this.score.runs}}</p>
  </template>
}
```

When a task is cancelled, execution stops at the current `await` point and the rest of the function body is skipped. Code after the last `await` simply never runs — it's not a race condition or an error, the task function just terminates silently. This means `@tracked` updates below a cancellation point are safe: you'll never get a stale result from an old instance overwriting a newer one. This is fundamentally different from Promise chains, where callbacks always fire once scheduled.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'

export default class ScoreExporter extends Component {
  @tracked exportProgress = 0

  exportData = task(async () => {
    const controller = new AbortController()

    try {
      this.exportProgress = 0
      const res = await fetch('/api/export/scores', {
        signal: controller.signal
      })
      const blob = await res.blob()
      this.exportProgress = 100
      return blob
    } finally {
      // ✅ This block runs whether task completes, errors, OR is cancelled
      controller.abort() // clean up the AbortController
      this.exportProgress = 0 // reset progress indicator
      console.log('Export task ended (complete/error/cancel)')
    }
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.exportData)}}>Export</button>
    <button {{on "click" (fn this.exportData.cancelAll)}}>Cancel</button>
    <progress value={{this.exportProgress}} max="100"></progress>
  </template>
}
```

Yes — `finally` in a task function always executes, even on cancellation. This makes `finally` the correct place for cleanup code: releasing locks, resetting progress indicators, aborting native fetch requests via `AbortController`, or closing WebSocket connections. The `try/catch` block does *not* catch cancellation (it's not an error), but `finally` reliably runs. This is the ember-concurrency equivalent of Rust's `Drop` trait or C#'s `using` statement — guaranteed cleanup regardless of exit path.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class MatchResultLoader extends Component {
  loadResult = task(async (matchId) => {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/result`)
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status}: Failed to load result`)
    return await res.json()
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.loadResult this.args.matchId)}}>Load</button>
    <button {{on "click" (fn this.loadResult.cancelAll)}}>Cancel</button>

    {{! Error: task threw — instance.error is set, isCancelled is false }}
    {{#if this.loadResult.last.error}}
      <p class="text-red-600">Error: {{this.loadResult.last.error.message}}</p>
    {{/if}}

    {{! Cancelled: task was cancelled — isCancelled is true, error is null }}
    {{#if this.loadResult.last.isCancelled}}
      <p class="text-gray-400">Cancelled</p>
    {{/if}}

    {{! Success }}
    {{#if this.loadResult.lastSuccessful}}
      <p>Winner: {{this.loadResult.lastSuccessful.value.winner}}</p>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```

A task instance has distinct states: `isError` (threw an exception), `isCancelled` (cancelled before completing), and `isSuccessful` (returned normally). When a task throws, `instance.error` is set and the error is accessible in templates. When cancelled, `instance.isCancelled` is `true` but `error` is `null` — cancellation is not an error. `task.lastSuccessful` excludes both errored and cancelled instances. `task.lastComplete` includes errored instances but excludes cancelled ones. This three-way distinction lets you build precise UI feedback.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class LiveScorePoller extends Component {
  // ✅ Looping task — self-cleaning, cancellation-safe
  pollLiveScore = task(async () => {
    while (true) {
      const res = await fetch('/api/live-score')
      const data = await res.json()
      console.log('Score:', data.runs, '/', data.wickets)
      await timeout(5000) // wait 5s before next poll
      // If task cancelled (component destroyed), loop exits here — no more fetches
    }
  })

  // ❌ setInterval — NOT self-cleaning, keeps running after component destroyed
  startInterval = () => {
    const id = setInterval(async () => {
      const data = await fetch('/api/live-score').then(r => r.json())
      // Runs forever — even after component is destroyed!
    }, 5000)
    // Must manually clearInterval in willDestroy — easy to forget
  }

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.pollLiveScore)}}>Start Live</button>
    <button {{on "click" (fn this.pollLiveScore.cancelAll)}}>Stop</button>
  </template>
}
```

A looping task with `timeout()` is superior to `setInterval` in three ways: (1) **automatic cleanup** — destroyed with the component, no `clearInterval` needed; (2) **sequential execution** — next poll only starts after the previous fetch completes, preventing overlapping requests; (3) **cancellable** — you can stop polling programmatically with `.cancelAll()`. `setInterval` fires at fixed wall-clock intervals regardless of how long the async work takes, can cause overlapping requests on slow networks, and must be manually cleared.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'
import { service } from '@ember/service'

export default class TournamentTable extends Component {
  @service store

  // ✅ Task wrapping Ember Data query — reactive, cancellable
  loadFixtures = task({ drop: true }, async (tournamentId) => {
    // store.query returns a Promise — awaitable inside a task
    const fixtures = await this.store.query('fixture', {
      filter: { tournament: tournamentId },
