`all()` from ember-concurrency is cancellation-aware — if the parent task is cancelled, all child promises are abandoned. Using multiple `perform()` calls in parallel has no coordination: if one fails or the parent is cancelled, the others continue running. `all()` also keeps the code flat and returns results in order, avoiding nested state management.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class QueueDemoComponent extends Component {
  // drop — queue capacity: 0. New performs are silently discarded
  saveScore = task({ drop: true }, async () => { /* ... */ })

  // enqueue — unlimited queue. All performs run in order, one at a time
  processDelivery = task({ enqueue: true }, async () => { /* ... */ })

  // restartable — queue capacity: 0 but cancels current. Only latest runs
  searchPlayer = task({ restartable: true }, async () => { /* ... */ })

  // keepLatest — queue capacity: 1. Latest queued replaces previous queued
  fetchInnings = task({ keepLatest: true }, async () => { /* ... */ })
}
```
Each modifier changes the queue behavior: `drop` has no queue (0 capacity) and discards new calls. `enqueue` has unlimited queue depth and serializes all calls. `restartable` has no queue but cancels the running instance for each new call. `keepLatest` keeps exactly one pending call in queue, replacing it if another arrives. Understanding this model helps you choose the right modifier for each async scenario.

