Use **ember-concurrency** by default in Ember apps. It integrates natively with Glimmer reactivity, Ember's test helpers, and component lifecycle. It covers debounce, polling, concurrency control, cancellation, and error handling with minimal API surface. Use **RxJS** only when you have complex multi-stream combinatorics that are genuinely cleaner with reactive operators, or when migrating an existing RxJS codebase. Adding RxJS to an Ember app purely for async management adds significant bundle size and learning curve with no advantage over ember-concurrency.

```gjs
// ✅ RECOMMENDED: task — gives cancellation, loading state, drop semantics
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class MatchFeedComponent extends Component {
  @tracked matches = []
  @tracked page = 1

  loadMoreMatches = task({ drop: true }, async () => {
    const newMatches = await fetch(`/api/matches?page=${this.page}`).then(r => r.json())
    this.matches = [...this.matches, ...newMatches]
    this.page += 1
  })

  setupObserver = (element) => {
    const observer = new IntersectionObserver(([entry]) => {
      if (entry.isIntersecting) this.loadMoreMatches.perform()
    })
    observer.observe(element)
  }

  <template>
    {{#each this.matches as |match|}}
      <div>{{match.title}}</div>
    {{/each}}
    {{#if this.loadMoreMatches.isRunning}}
      <p>Loading more matches...</p>
    {{/if}}
    <div {{did-insert this.setupObserver}}></div>
  </template>
}
```

Use a `drop` task for infinite scroll because rapid scroll triggers won't stack duplicate fetches — the second call is silently dropped while the first is running. A plain `async` function has no guard against concurrent calls, so fast scrolling could fire multiple overlapping requests and cause out-of-order appends. The task also gives you `isRunning` and `last.error` for free, reducing boilerplate. Use IntersectionObserver only as the trigger mechanism, not as the async executor itself.

