Native `loading='lazy'` is zero-cost and works perfectly for public, unauthenticated images — use it by default for player thumbnails, team logos, and venue photos. Reach for a task only when the image fetch requires authentication headers, needs a loading spinner tied to `isRunning`, requires a Blob URL transformation, or needs retry logic on failure. Tasks add complexity; reserve them for when native browser behavior is insufficient.

```gjs
// ✅ RECOMMENDED: task in AuthService — centralized, cancellable, no duplicate refresh
import Service from '@ember/service'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class AuthService extends Service {
  accessToken = null

  refreshToken = task({ drop: true }, async () => {
    const res = await fetch('/api/auth/refresh', {
      method: 'POST',
      body: JSON.stringify({ token: this.refreshTokenValue })
    }).then(r => r.json())
    this.accessToken = res.accessToken
    return res.accessToken
  })

  async getValidToken() {
    if (this.isExpired()) {
      return this.refreshToken.perform()
    }
    return this.accessToken
  }
}
```

A `drop` task on a service is the right pattern because multiple simultaneous API calls can all detect token expiry at the same time — with `drop`, only one refresh request is ever in-flight and subsequent callers wait for the same promise rather than firing duplicate refresh requests. An adapter interceptor runs per-request and cannot prevent the thundering-herd problem without a shared lock. The service task acts as that shared lock naturally. Any component or service can call `authService.getValidToken()` safely.

```gjs
// ✅ RECOMMENDED: restartable task for live suggestions UX
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class PlayerSearchComponent extends Component {
  @tracked query = ''
  @tracked suggestions = []

  searchPlayers = task({ restartable: true }, async (query) => {
    await timeout(300) // debounce
    if (query.length < 2) return
    this.suggestions = await fetch(`/api/players?q=${query}`).then(r => r.json())
  })

  handleInput = (e) => {
    this.query = e.target.value
    this.searchPlayers.perform(this.query)
  }

  <template>
    <input value={{this.query}} {{on "input" this.handleInput}} placeholder="Search player..." />
    {{#if this.searchPlayers.isRunning}}<span>Searching...</span>{{/if}}
    {{#each this.suggestions as |player|}}
      <div>{{player.name}}</div>
    {{/each}}
  </template>
}
```

A restartable task with a `timeout(300)` debounce is the correct choice for search-as-you-type UX — each keystroke restarts the task, cancelling the previous, so only the final settled query hits the server. Server-side-only search (full form submit) forces the user to press Enter and see a full page reload, which is unacceptable for modern sports apps where instant player lookup is expected. Use server-only search only when queries are complex, require authentication scoping, or the dataset is too large for incremental suggestions.

