```

If all the data you need is already in memory (passed as `@args` or in a service), generate the CSV synchronously — it is instant and a task adds no value. Use a task when the export requires an async step first: fetching the complete scorecard from an API, generating a report on the server, or waiting for a background computation. The deciding question is: is there any async work? If no, use `@action`. If yes, use a task.

```gjs
// ✅ RECOMMENDED: Web Worker for CPU-heavy simulation, task to manage it
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class MatchSimulatorComponent extends Component {
  @tracked result = null

  runSimulation = task(async (matchConfig) => {
    const result = await new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
      const worker = new Worker('/workers/match-simulator.js')
      worker.postMessage(matchConfig)
      worker.onmessage = (e) => { worker.terminate(); resolve(e.data) }
      worker.onerror = (e) => { worker.terminate(); reject(e) }
    })
    this.result = result
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" (fn (perform this.runSimulation) this.args.matchConfig)}}>
      Simulate Match
    </button>
    {{#if this.runSimulation.isRunning}}<p>Simulating...</p>{{/if}}
    {{#if this.result}}<p>Winner: {{this.result.winner}}</p>{{/if}}
  </template>
}
```

An ember-concurrency task runs on the main thread — if your simulation loops through 120 overs with probability calculations, it will freeze the UI for seconds, dropping frames and making the app unresponsive. Web Workers run on a separate thread, keeping the UI smooth. Use a task to manage the Worker lifecycle (start, await, handle errors, expose `isRunning`) while the Worker does the heavy lifting. This is the correct division: tasks manage async coordination, Workers own CPU-intensive computation.

