Hardcoded config is the right choice during feature development — no network dependency, instant, easy to toggle. Switch to a task-based server fetch when you need real user segmentation (50% see compact, 50% see expanded), persistent assignment per user, and analytics tracking per variant. Always set a safe default variant before the task resolves so the component renders immediately without a blank state. If your A/B system uses a client-side SDK that loads synchronously, you may not need a task at all.

```gjs
// ✅ OPTION A — embedded in initial response (prefer for small, always-visible data)
// GET /api/match/:id → includes players[].bio inline
// No task needed — data is in @args immediately

// ✅ OPTION B — lazy task (use for large bios or rarely-expanded profiles)
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class PlayerProfileCardComponent extends Component {
  @tracked bio = null
  @tracked isExpanded = false

  loadBio = task(async () => {
    this.bio = await fetch(`/api/player/${this.args.player.id}/bio`).then(r => r.json())
  })

  toggleExpand = () => {
    this.isExpanded = !this.isExpanded
    if (this.isExpanded && !this.bio) {
      this.loadBio.perform()
    }
  }

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" this.toggleExpand}}>{{@player.name}}</button>
    {{#if this.isExpanded}}
      {{#if this.loadBio.isRunning}}<p>Loading bio...</p>{{/if}}
      {{#if this.bio}}<p>{{this.bio.summary}}</p>{{/if}}
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```

Embed bio data in the initial response when it is small (under ~2KB), always displayed, and needed immediately on page load — fewer round trips is always faster. Use a lazy task when bios are long (career history, statistics), only revealed on user interaction (expand button), and the page shows 11+ players simultaneously (embedding 11 full bios bloats the initial payload). The on-demand task pattern is ideal for progressive disclosure: show player name and stats upfront, fetch rich bio only when the user explicitly asks for it.

