ember-concurrency's `all()` is like `Promise.all()` but cancels the remaining `TaskInstance` siblings if any one of them fails or is cancelled. With `Promise.all`, a failing task still leaves sibling tasks running — wasting network resources and potentially causing race conditions. Always use `all()` from `ember-concurrency` when coordinating multiple tasks.

